  "editorial": {
    "headline": "First place on the line. NYY takes it.",
    "subheadline": "CWS 5, NYY 10. Top of the division changes hands — or firms up.",
    "lead_angle": "José Caballero’s two-run single in the fifth inning ripped open a tight contest, lifting the New York Yankees to a 10-5 victory over the Chicago White Sox at Yankee Stadium. Southpaw Carlos Rodón picked up the win for New York, scattering hits through much of his outing, while Anthony Kay was tagged with the loss for Chicago. Caballero's hit gave the Yankees a comfortable lead.\n\nThe game turned decisively in the bottom of the fifth. The Yankees, clinging to a 4-3 advantage, started to rally. Ali Sánchez drove in a run to extend the lead, and moments later, José Caballero stepped to the plate. His base hit plated two more, pushing the score to 7-3. The Bronx Bombers continued to pile on, adding two additional runs before the inning concluded, seizing a commanding 9-3 lead.\n\nChicago White Sox second baseman Colson Montgomery was a bright spot for the visitors despite the defeat, belting two home runs and accounting for four runs batted in on two hits in four at-bats. The New York Yankees’ triumph solidifies their standing at the top of the American League East, providing crucial breathing room in the season’s pennant race.",
